<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Flyght on 04-01-2001 03:08 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Do that many people actually keep Complete Heal up all the time?  Don't you find it's a very situational spell?  

My line up has never had Complete Heal as a regular spell, unless there is a warrior in a controlled environment /shrug (swap DL for CH)

1) Remedy
2) Celestial Healing
3) Divine Light
4) Root
5) Stun (lvl 5, no dmg, no broken mez)
6) Reckoning
7) DA
8) DB

Almost always the same, swap stun/DL when buffs are needed.  

On Raids I may take out Reckoning for Heroic Bond as group heal, as it won't land anyway heh (when lures are the only thing landing, a cleric nuke just is not needed lol).  When gating mobs are a problem, I find room for another stun.

As for Complete, sometimes even when there is a Warrior I'll swap it in and out only when I need it.  Often it is my downtime heal, I don't like dropping a Cheal in the middle of a fight, would rather drop a celest and wait another 30-45 secs until the fight is almost over to drop the complete.  

This may also be from the environment I play on, as casters are more popular than tanks on PvP servers.  

If there is a warrior and no enchanter (rare) I'll put CH up.  With an enchanter and c2 feeding me, I wouldnt even bother with the risk of CH for some extra efficiency.  There is nothing worse than waiting for the warrior to get low enough for the Complete to be actually worthwhile, and right as you start casting, the mob turns to the chanter/wiz/rogue and lays them to waste..  Especially when with 2 celests the tank would never have dipped under 70-80 health, while you are sitting medding back to full ready for a cast.

Of course, our roles change as group makeup changes, so I would never be so ignorant as to say Complete Heal is worthless, just in my opinion it's situational and rarely used in the groups I regularly hunt in.

Flyght</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
